<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-04-11T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-04-11T19:00:00-05:00" n="606" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d606">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3333: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moore</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-04-11T19:00:00-05:00">April 11, 1929—7
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:55 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>70. This afternoon I saw President Leguia after his conference with
                            Ambassador Figueroa. The conference turned out as predicted in my 68,
                            April 11, 4 a.m. The details regarding the proposed port were turned
                            over to President Leguia, who in turn gave them to Engineer Seeley for
                            examination and report.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>